@page "/components"

<PageTitle>Components</PageTitle>

<W3Container Class="w3-padding-32">
    <h1>W3Css.Blazor Components</h1>
    <DocPager PreviousHref="installation" PreviousText="Installation" NextHref="components/defaults" NextText="Defaults" />

    <p class="w3-large">Each component topic follows the W3.CSS documentation pattern: short introduction, live examples, copyable code, parameter reference, and related links.</p>

    <section class="doc-section">
        <h2>Component Categories</h2>
        <p>The catalog is grouped around how a team builds real pages: foundation, layout, content, data, forms, navigation, feedback, overlays, media, and utility styling. The categories borrow the mental model used by larger Blazor libraries while keeping each W3Css.Blazor component tied to W3.CSS classes, native HTML, or Blazor state.</p>

        @foreach (var category in Categories)
        {
            <section class="doc-section">
                <h3>@category.Name</h3>
                <p class="doc-muted">@category.Description</p>
                <W3Table Striped="true" Bordered="true" Hoverable="true" Responsive="true" aria-label="@($"{category.Name} component topics")">
                    <thead>
                        <tr>
                            <th>Topic</th>
                            <th>Use</th>
                            <th>Status</th>
                        </tr>
                    </thead>
                    <tbody>
                        @foreach (var topic in category.Topics)
                        {
                            <tr>
                                <td><NavLink href="@topic.Href">@topic.Name</NavLink></td>
                                <td>@topic.Use</td>
                                <td>@topic.Status</td>
                            </tr>
                        }
                    </tbody>
                </W3Table>
            </section>
        }
    </section>

    <section class="doc-section">
        <h2>Product Readiness Backlog</h2>
        <W3Panel Color="W3Color.PaleYellow" TextColor="W3Color.Black" LeftBar="true" Border="true" Round="W3Round.Medium">
            <p>These candidates enrich site and app building without changing the vendored W3.CSS file. Each should compose existing components, W3.CSS classes, native HTML inputs, or small Blazor-owned state before adding any isolated CSS.</p>
        </W3Panel>

        <W3Table Striped="true" Bordered="true" Hoverable="true" Responsive="true" aria-label="Product readiness backlog">
            <thead>
                <tr>
                    <th>Candidate</th>
                    <th>Category</th>
                    <th>Why It Matters</th>
                    <th>W3.CSS-First Approach</th>
                    <th>Priority</th>
                </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
                @if (ExpansionBacklog.Length == 0)
                {
                    <tr>
                        <td colspan="5">No low-risk second-round component gaps are currently queued.</td>
                    </tr>
                }
                else
                {
                    @foreach (var item in ExpansionBacklog)
                    {
                        <tr>
                            <td><code>@item.Name</code></td>
                            <td>@item.Category</td>
                            <td>@item.Why</td>
                            <td>@item.Approach</td>
                            <td>@item.Priority</td>
                        </tr>
                    }
                }
            </tbody>
        </W3Table>
    </section>

    <section class="doc-section">
        <h2>Page Format</h2>
        <W3Panel Color="W3Color.PaleBlue" TextColor="W3Color.Black" LeftBar="true" Border="true" Round="W3Round.Medium">
            <p>Component pages keep the instruction and examples together so readers can learn the Blazor API without jumping between separate reference and example pages.</p>
        </W3Panel>

        <ul class="w3-ul w3-border w3-white">
            <li><strong>Introduction</strong> explains when to use the component.</li>
            <li><strong>Examples</strong> show the rendered component and the Razor markup beside it.</li>
            <li><strong>Parameter Reference</strong> lists typed parameters, defaults, and generated W3.CSS behavior.</li>
            <li><strong>Related W3.CSS</strong> links back to the original CSS topic where it helps.</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="doc-section">
        <h2>Next Topics</h2>
        <div class="w3-bar w3-border w3-white">
            <NavLink class="w3-bar-item w3-button" href="components/defaults">Defaults</NavLink>
            <NavLink class="w3-bar-item w3-button" href="components/fonts">Fonts</NavLink>
            <NavLink class="w3-bar-item w3-button" href="components/colors">Colors</NavLink>
            <NavLink class="w3-bar-item w3-button" href="components/color-schemes">Color Schemes</NavLink>
            <NavLink class="w3-bar-item w3-button" href="components/trends">Trends</NavLink>
            <NavLink class="w3-bar-item w3-button" href="components/case-study">Case Study</NavLink>
            <NavLink class="w3-bar-item w3-button" href="components/material-design">Material Design</NavLink>
            <NavLink class="w3-bar-item w3-button" href="components/versions">Versions</NavLink>
            <NavLink class="w3-bar-item w3-button" href="components/app-shell">App Shell</NavLink>
            <NavLink class="w3-bar-item w3-button" href="components/app-bar">App Bar</NavLink>
        </div>
    </section>

    <DocPager PreviousHref="installation" PreviousText="Installation" NextHref="components/defaults" NextText="Defaults" />
</W3Container>

